                covered by layers of sand, silt, and rock, subject to heat and pressure, and eventually turned into a
                type of
                fossil fuel that is refined into usable products including gasoline, diesel, liquefied petroleum gases,
                and
                feedstock for the petrochemical industry.

                Crude oil is a nonrenewable resource, which means that it can't be replaced naturally at the rate we
                consume it
                and is, therefore, a limited resource.</p>

